textDelta: What was the purpose of the Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions? The Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions was signed by President Bush and President Putin in Moscow on May 24, 2002. The treaty required the United States and Russia to reduce their strategic nuclear arsenals to no more than 2,200 operationally deployed nuclear warheads on no more than 700 ICBMs, SLBMs, and strategic bombers. The treaty also required the United States and Russia to reduce their non-deployed strategic nuclear warheads to no more than 2,200.
